596
00:29:11,970 --> 00:29:15,210
- So GuardDuty has multiple
engines that it uses

597
00:29:15,210 --> 00:29:18,183
to handle different detection scenarios.

598
00:29:19,260 --> 00:29:22,533
The first engine we have
is a hash-based one,

599
00:29:23,610 --> 00:29:25,650
and we use that engine primarily

600
00:29:25,650 --> 00:29:27,630
to suppress false positives

601
00:29:27,630 --> 00:29:31,233
so we can exclude the
one file and no others.

602
00:29:33,300 --> 00:29:37,680
We also use this engine
for responding quickly.

603
00:29:37,680 --> 00:29:38,970
For example, if there's an outbreak

604
00:29:38,970 --> 00:29:42,210
and we can add detection very quickly,

605
00:29:42,210 --> 00:29:45,243
and we can respond within
minutes instead of hours.

606
00:29:49,080 --> 00:29:50,850
The engine itself is quite fast.

607
00:29:50,850 --> 00:29:54,813
We found some ways to accelerate
our hashing operation.

608
00:29:56,790 --> 00:29:58,590
And the engine itself is resilient

609
00:29:58,590 --> 00:30:00,633
to minor changes in the file.

610
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:05,040
And what I mean by that is that typically,

611
00:30:05,040 --> 00:30:08,040
we consider a file to be
a solid block of bytes,

612
00:30:08,040 --> 00:30:13,040
and so hash just from end
to end to get a single hash.

613
00:30:17,850 --> 00:30:21,180
But there can be cases where a file has a,

614
00:30:21,180 --> 00:30:22,710
instead of being a solid block of bytes,

615
00:30:22,710 --> 00:30:24,990
there might be some squishy
bit right in the middle.

616
00:30:24,990 --> 00:30:28,113
It might have a URL or
username/password combination.

617
00:30:29,370 --> 00:30:31,800
And in that case, our engine is differing

618
00:30:31,800 --> 00:30:34,620
from the traditional implementation,

619
00:30:34,620 --> 00:30:38,043
because it can be told to
hash around the variable part.

620
00:30:40,530 --> 00:30:44,400
Similarly, if a file has content

621
00:30:44,400 --> 00:30:46,680
at the end that is variable,

622
00:30:46,680 --> 00:30:48,780
perhaps there's an appended configuration,

623
00:30:49,650 --> 00:30:52,440
then our engine can be told
to hash up to the point

624
00:30:52,440 --> 00:30:56,370
where the variable content starts,

625
00:30:56,370 --> 00:30:59,190
which means that you can add
any number of additional bytes,

626
00:30:59,190 --> 00:31:02,910
you can change any values
within the variable section

627
00:31:02,910 --> 00:31:04,760
and we'll still have a constant hash.

628
00:31:05,820 --> 00:31:09,630
So for the people that,
you know, bad actors

629
00:31:09,630 --> 00:31:12,240
that are getting their
sites taken down quickly

630
00:31:12,240 --> 00:31:15,603
and they keep cycling, we'll
still have detection for these.

631
00:31:18,090 --> 00:31:21,120
The next engine we have is
a pattern matching engine.

632
00:31:21,120 --> 00:31:23,250
In the event that hashing is not suitable

633
00:31:23,250 --> 00:31:28,080
because there might be multiple
changes throughout the file,

634
00:31:28,080 --> 00:31:30,900
or if a file is very, very large,

635
00:31:30,900 --> 00:31:33,180
but the really interesting
part is right at the front,

636
00:31:33,180 --> 00:31:37,023
then we'll use the pattern
matching engine for that.

637
00:31:39,720 --> 00:31:42,390
The engine is very flexible,

638
00:31:42,390 --> 00:31:45,780
it supports traditional
signature-based scanning,

639
00:31:45,780 --> 00:31:48,360
just doing straight byte comparisons.

640
00:31:48,360 --> 00:31:50,370
But we can do more than that.

641
00:31:50,370 --> 00:31:54,960
We can perform conditional evaluations

642
00:31:54,960 --> 00:31:56,973
up to a certain point in the file.

643
00:31:57,900 --> 00:31:59,880
We can perform frequency analysis

644
00:31:59,880 --> 00:32:02,520
of the bytes we've seen
up to a certain point,

645
00:32:02,520 --> 00:32:05,550
and we can even extract
bit level characteristics

646
00:32:05,550 --> 00:32:08,313
of the file for very fine
grain pattern matching.

647
00:32:11,100 --> 00:32:12,870
The engine is very expressive,

648
00:32:12,870 --> 00:32:15,330
so the intent of a detection

649
00:32:15,330 --> 00:32:17,580
is very clear for the next engineer

650
00:32:17,580 --> 00:32:20,760
who has to perhaps extend
an existing detection

651
00:32:20,760 --> 00:32:22,950
or if they're the ones
having to do the code review

652
00:32:22,950 --> 00:32:24,603
for an existing detection.

653
00:32:27,360 --> 00:32:30,450
We use this engine primarily
for specific detections

654
00:32:30,450 --> 00:32:34,443
where the code is constant
across replicants.

655
00:32:35,430 --> 00:32:39,300
And here's an example from actual malware.

656
00:32:39,300 --> 00:32:44,300
This code will execute arbitrary
commands received remotely

657
00:32:44,520 --> 00:32:46,143
without any user interaction.

658
00:32:47,310 --> 00:32:49,950
And for us, this quite a simple example.

659
00:32:49,950 --> 00:32:54,950
It's a single detection,
but there also can be cases

660
00:32:55,260 --> 00:32:58,350
where we wanna use the
engine for generic detections

661
00:32:58,350 --> 00:33:03,350
where multiple variants of the same sample

662
00:33:05,280 --> 00:33:08,763
differ only slightly, but
otherwise functionally equivalent.

663
00:33:11,250 --> 00:33:15,180
Here's an example of an actual malware,

664
00:33:15,180 --> 00:33:16,530
just a snippet of the code.

665
00:33:17,550 --> 00:33:19,860
This malware uses a polymorphic engine

666
00:33:19,860 --> 00:33:23,433
to change its appearance
from replicant to replicant.

667
00:33:25,980 --> 00:33:30,980
And the engine is able to
insert random characters

668
00:33:31,290 --> 00:33:32,970
in the decryptor body

669
00:33:32,970 --> 00:33:36,393
and also change the variable
names to random strings.

670
00:33:38,100 --> 00:33:39,600
Here's another example where you can see

671
00:33:39,600 --> 00:33:42,723
the constant portions
are becoming smaller.

672
00:33:44,460 --> 00:33:45,840
And here's the extreme example

673
00:33:45,840 --> 00:33:47,700
where the constant
portions have been reduced

674
00:33:47,700 --> 00:33:49,860
to the smallest possible length

675
00:33:49,860 --> 00:33:51,120
and all the variable names

676
00:33:51,120 --> 00:33:53,070
have been replaced with random strings.

677
00:33:54,090 --> 00:33:56,400
And despite the difference
between the first example

678
00:33:56,400 --> 00:34:00,930
and the last one, it's still
a single detection for us.

679
00:34:00,930 --> 00:34:04,083
That gives a sense of just
how powerful this engine is.

680
00:34:07,350 --> 00:34:10,380
The next engine we have is
a machine learning engine,

681
00:34:10,380 --> 00:34:13,200
and our focus with machine learning

682
00:34:13,200 --> 00:34:15,690
is cryptocurrency miners.

683
00:34:15,690 --> 00:34:18,540
The reason for that is because
within our environment,

684
00:34:18,540 --> 00:34:21,123
cryptocurrency miners are a big problem.

685
00:34:22,380 --> 00:34:25,263
And you might be wondering
how big of a problem it is.

686
00:34:27,780 --> 00:34:32,520
If we look at this table here, we can see

687
00:34:32,520 --> 00:34:35,120
how quickly a cryptocurrency
miner can be installed.

688
00:34:36,060 --> 00:34:39,510
We went from a misconfigured state

689
00:34:39,510 --> 00:34:43,140
to a compromised state in less
than four and a half days,

690
00:34:43,140 --> 00:34:47,040
which means that the
compromised instance was found

691
00:34:47,040 --> 00:34:50,040
in its pristine state almost immediately

692
00:34:50,040 --> 00:34:52,940
and the miner was installed
very, very quickly after that.

693
00:34:56,130 --> 00:35:00,600
If we consider from a dynamic
analysis point of view,

694
00:35:00,600 --> 00:35:03,330
over 60% of compromised workloads

695
00:35:03,330 --> 00:35:04,650
involve cryptocurrency mining

696
00:35:04,650 --> 00:35:07,023
as part of that post exploitation event.

697
00:35:07,860 --> 00:35:09,390
And in fact, cryptocurrency mining

698
00:35:09,390 --> 00:35:12,990
is the most common post
compromise activity

699
00:35:12,990 --> 00:35:16,413
that we see in a dynamic
detection scenario.

700
00:35:18,060 --> 00:35:20,730
But coming back to the static analysis,

701
00:35:20,730 --> 00:35:25,730
I took one week's worth of scan
results that had detections.

702
00:35:26,070 --> 00:35:27,960
Of those scan results,

703
00:35:27,960 --> 00:35:32,010
I took 8,000 samples entirely randomly.

704
00:35:32,010 --> 00:35:35,370
And of those 8,000 detections we had,

705
00:35:35,370 --> 00:35:37,833
45% of them were cryptocurrency miners.

706
00:35:39,480 --> 00:35:42,570
Now not all of those were unique,

707
00:35:42,570 --> 00:35:46,050
but even if 90% of them were identical,

708
00:35:46,050 --> 00:35:48,930
that still leaves over 300 unique samples

709
00:35:48,930 --> 00:35:51,840
that someone would have to
add detection for manually

710
00:35:51,840 --> 00:35:54,690
from this subset week-over-week,

711
00:35:54,690 --> 00:35:57,453
if we were to do this one at a time.

712
00:35:58,740 --> 00:35:59,990
So that's a huge problem.

713
00:36:01,050 --> 00:36:04,173
But fortunately for us, we
have a machine learning model,

714
00:36:05,190 --> 00:36:07,170
and I would love to say it's so awesome

715
00:36:07,170 --> 00:36:09,390
that it detects all of these,

716
00:36:09,390 --> 00:36:11,163
but it's not, at least not yet,

717
00:36:12,030 --> 00:36:14,580
but still, it's doing some
very heavy lifting for us,

718
00:36:14,580 --> 00:36:17,010
and for the ones that it doesn't detect,

719
00:36:17,010 --> 00:36:18,930
we have our patent matching engine

720
00:36:18,930 --> 00:36:21,130
and the hashing engine
to clean up the rest.

721
00:36:23,880 --> 00:36:26,970
The next engine we have
is a third-party engine.

722
00:36:26,970 --> 00:36:29,853
We receive this engine as
an SDK from the vendor,

723
00:36:30,870 --> 00:36:33,120
and it runs as part of
our regular scan flow.

724
00:36:34,050 --> 00:36:37,353
But we run this engine in an
entirely isolated instance.

725
00:36:38,250 --> 00:36:41,010
It's not able to connect
with the cloud provider,

726
00:36:41,010 --> 00:36:43,950
it's not able to connect
to the internet at all.

727
00:36:43,950 --> 00:36:45,540
The only thing we get out of the instance

728
00:36:45,540 --> 00:36:49,320
is the finding results, and
we are very careful about

729
00:36:49,320 --> 00:36:52,290
what we will accept
from the finding results

730
00:36:52,290 --> 00:36:54,963
to minimize the chance
of exfiltration of data.

731
00:36:58,260 --> 00:37:01,830
We use this engine primarily
for historical detections,

732
00:37:01,830 --> 00:37:05,190
because the vendor has seen many samples

733
00:37:05,190 --> 00:37:07,050
that we might never see.

734
00:37:07,050 --> 00:37:10,800
We don't automatically
collect samples from customers

735
00:37:10,800 --> 00:37:13,680
and we don't share these
samples with the vendor.

736
00:37:13,680 --> 00:37:16,590
So in the event that a
customer is not willing

737
00:37:16,590 --> 00:37:18,330
to share a sample with us,

738
00:37:18,330 --> 00:37:20,430
then we might never see the sample at all.

739
00:37:22,603 --> 00:37:25,740
The SDK also offers heuristic detections,

740
00:37:25,740 --> 00:37:29,100
and they use a machine learning
model for this as well.

741
00:37:29,100 --> 00:37:32,280
We are working to develop
our own heuristics specific

742
00:37:32,280 --> 00:37:35,160
to our environment, but at least for now,

743
00:37:35,160 --> 00:37:36,510
these existing heuristics

744
00:37:36,510 --> 00:37:38,403
are a very powerful baseline for us.

745
00:37:41,310 --> 00:37:44,880
We also get passes in this
SDK for common file formats

746
00:37:44,880 --> 00:37:47,703
such as archives, images and documents.

747
00:37:48,540 --> 00:37:50,760
Again, we're working on
our own passes specific

748
00:37:50,760 --> 00:37:53,463
to our environment to get
better scanning performance,

749
00:37:54,660 --> 00:37:56,580
but we also have file formats

750
00:37:56,580 --> 00:37:58,230
that the vendor might never see

751
00:37:58,230 --> 00:38:00,450
because we don't share the samples.

752
00:38:00,450 --> 00:38:03,173
And so we're working on
specific parsers for those two.

753
00:38:09,660 --> 00:38:13,770
So that covers our static
detection for EC2 and S3.

754
00:38:13,770 --> 00:38:15,840
And Mikaelly, my co-presenter,

755
00:38:15,840 --> 00:38:18,240
will talk more about a
specific use case for S3,

756
00:38:19,401 --> 00:38:21,551
but we have more than
just static scanning.

757
00:38:23,220 --> 00:38:25,263
We also have a runtime service.

758
00:38:27,720 --> 00:38:30,870
This runtime service runs on the instance.

759
00:38:30,870 --> 00:38:35,700
It has system-wide
visibility into everything

760
00:38:35,700 --> 00:38:38,250
that's happening as it happens.

761
00:38:38,250 --> 00:38:40,680
We get file system and network events,

762
00:38:40,680 --> 00:38:41,970
and there's also container aware,

763
00:38:41,970 --> 00:38:45,783
so we can see inside AKS and ECS.

764
00:38:48,060 --> 00:38:52,230
We collect events from
the system into signals

765
00:38:52,230 --> 00:38:55,130
and a collection of signals
get correlated into a finding.

766
00:38:57,780 --> 00:39:00,150
Here's an example of a finding

767
00:39:00,150 --> 00:39:02,940
using our latest extended
threat detection,

768
00:39:02,940 --> 00:39:06,180
which was presented at an
earlier talk this morning.

769
00:39:06,180 --> 00:39:09,390
You can see the level of
detail that we have here.

